<section xml:id="section-activity-clo6">
  <title>Activity for CLO-6</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-clo6-review">
    <title>Conceptual Review</title>
    <p>
      You can test your learning from the video (and your own
      background knowledge) with the following review questions.
      Conceptual questions on quizes may be taken from these review
      questions. 
    </p>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is a derivative?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          A derivative is a measure of the rate of growth or rate of
          change of a function. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is a differential equation?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          A differential equation is an equation which involves a
          function and its derivative. It is relationship between the
          current value of a function and its rate of change. The
          <sq>answer</sq> to a differential equation is a function. A
          differential equation is implicitly asking <sq>What function
          satisfies this property</sq>? (That is, in the same way that
          an algebraic equation is implicitly asking <sq>What number
          satisfied this property</sq>?) 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What does it mean to solve a differential equation?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Solving a differential equation means finding the function
          which behaves according to the differential equation. Very
          often, a differential equation is an observation about the
          world, but the actual function is unknown. Solving the
          differential equation is discovering what function actually
          describes the situation. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          How is percentage growth a differential equation?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Percentage growth is implicity a relationship between a
          growth rate and the current value. If I say that a
          population grows at <m>5\%</m>, that means that the growth
          rate, how much the function is increasing in a unit of time,
          is measured as <m>\frac{5}{100}</m> of the current value.
          This can be translated directly into mathematical symbols. 
          <md>
            \frac{dp}{dt} = \frac{5}{100} p(t) 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is the Malthusian model?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The Malthusian model is another name for percentage growth.
          For our purpsoes, it is specifically talking about the
          differential equation version of percentage growth. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Why can we reasonably talk about differential equation as
          translations of observations stated in ordinary language?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Up to a certain point, mathematical symbols are translations of
          regular language. This is particular true for growth rates.
          Often in a situation in the world, we can collect data and
          make an observation about the growth rate, such as the
          observation of percentage growth. We get some
          regular-language statement about growth: <sq>this
          population seems to growth at a roughly consistent seven
          percent each year</sq>. This is already a mathematical
          claim<mdash/>we just need to state it in mathematical
          symbols instead of English word. This is why we can treat a
          differential equation as a translation.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What one important piece of information about a function is
          missing from a differential equation?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The differential equation tells how a function changes, but
          not where it starts. Some kind of starting value is missing
          from a differential equation. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-malthusian">
    <title>Calculation Questions: Malthusian Model</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write the Malthusian model for <m>4.3\%</m> percentage
          growth and a starting value of <m>p(0) = 1436</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The percentage become the constant on the right side of the
          differential equation.
          <md>
            \frac{dp}{dt} = \frac{43}{1000} p(t)
          </md>
          The initial value is important, but it doesn't show up in
          the differential equation.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write the Malthusian model for <m>4\%</m> percentage
          decay and a starting value of <m>p(0) = 10^5</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The percentage become the constant on the right side of the
          differential equation. Since this is decay, not growth, the
          coefficient is negative. 
          <md>
            \frac{dp}{dt} = \frac{-4}{100} p(t)
          </md>
          The initial value is important, but it doesn't show up in
          the differential equation.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write the Malthusian model for no growth at all 
          growth and a starting value of <m>p(0) = 435</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The percentage become the constant on the right side of the
          differential equation. Since the constant is zero, the right
          side is multiplication of zero by the function, which is
          just zero. 
          <md>
            \frac{dp}{dt} = 0 
          </md>
          The initial value is important, but it doesn't show up in
          the differential equation.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-translation">
    <title>Calculation Questions: Translations</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Translate the following statement into a differential
          equation: the rate of change is proportional to the square
          of the current value of a population. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I follow the pattern of the Malthusian model. The left side
          is the derivative, which translates the rate of change. The
          right is the square of the function, which is the current
          value. I include a proportionality constant <m>\alpha</m>.
          <md>
            \frac{dp}{dt} = \alpha (p(t))^2
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Translate the following statement into a differential
          equation: the rate of change is proportional to the cube
          root of the current value of a population. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I follow the pattern of the Malthusian model. The left side
          is the derivative, which translates the rate of change. The
          right is the cube root of the function, which is the current
          value. I include a proportionality constant <m>\alpha</m>.
          <md>
            \frac{dp}{dt} = \alpha \sqrt[3]{p(t)} 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Translate the following statement into a differential
          equation: the rate of change is proportional to the sum of
          the reciprocal of the current value and another constant. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I follow the pattern of the Malthusian model. The left side
          is the derivative, which translates the rate of change. The
          right is the sum of the function and a constant, which i
          call <m>\beta</m>. 
          I include a proportionality constant <m>\alpha</m>.
          <md>
            \frac{dp}{dt} = \alpha \left( \frac{1}{p(t) + \beta
            \right) 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
</section>
